        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(sessions): preserve Media* index alignment when reading user-turn fields",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nThe inbound-media **writer** pads missing values with `\"\"` to keep the parallel `MediaPaths` / `MediaUrls` / `MediaTypes` arrays index-aligned, but the user-turn-transcript **reader** compacted those `\"\"` holes with `.filter(Boolean)` before indexing. The two arrays then drift out of alignment, so a later attachment's content-type (or URL) is assigned to an **earlier** attachment in the persisted transcript.\n\nRelated to #94255 (filed separately so it can be reviewed/rated on its own; not auto-closing this PR's merge so the issue can stand independently).\n\n## Change\n\n`normalizeOptionalTextArray` in `src/sessions/user-turn-transcript.ts` no longer compacts. It now maps each entry to a normalized string or `undefined` and returns `(string | undefined)[]`, preserving the writer's `\"\"` alignment holes (which normalize to `undefined`) so index `i` keeps referring to the same attachment.\n\nThe downstream builder (`buildPersistedUserTurnMediaInputsFromFields`) already does per-index `??` lookups (`types[index] ?? (index === 0 ? singleType : undefined)`) and derives `mediaCount` from `Math.max(paths.length, urls.length, ...)`, so it treats an `undefined` hole as \"absent\" with no further change — and `mediaCount` is now the true attachment count instead of a post-compaction shrink.\n\n**Reviewer decision points:**\n- Return type widened from `string[]` to `(string | undefined)[]`. The only call site is the builder above; the `paths[index]`/`urls[index]`/`types[index]` lookups already tolerate `undefined` via `??`, and the `if (!mediaPath && !url) continue;` guard skips pure-hole rows.\n- No change to the single-field fallbacks (`MediaPath`/`MediaUrl`/`MediaType` at index 0).\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n**Behavior addressed:** An inbound media turn with two attachments where the first lacks a content-type (`MediaTypes = [\"\", \"image/png\"]`) — the persisted reader assigned `image/png` to the typeless first attachment instead of to the second.\n\n**Real environment tested:** openclaw worktree at HEAD of `main` (`a7f96847ce`) on macOS, Node v26.0.0, exercising the real exported `buildPersistedUserTurnMediaInputsFromFields` reader (no mocks) against the actual writer wire format `MediaTypes=[\"\",\"image/png\"]`.\n\n**Exact steps or command run after this patch:** added a temporary spec calling the real reader and printed its output, run via the repo's vitest with `node` so console output surfaces:\n\n```\nnode_modules/.bin/vitest run src/sessions/_proof.test.ts --config vitest.config.ts --disable-console-intercept\n```\n\n**Evidence after fix:** real reader console output, copied verbatim:\n\n```\nINPUT MediaPaths= [\"/media/a.bin\",\"/media/b.png\"]\nINPUT MediaTypes= [\"\",\"image/png\"]\nOUT /media/a.bin => undefined\nOUT /media/b.png => image/png\n```\n\nFor contrast, the same real reader on the pre-patch source produced the misaligned output:\n\n```\nOUT /media/a.bin => image/png\nOUT /media/b.png => image/png\n```\n\n**Observed result after fix:** `/media/a.bin` now resolves to `undefined` (no false content-type borrowed from the next attachment), and `/media/b.png` keeps its own `image/png`. Before the patch `/media/a.bin` was wrongly labeled `image/png`. Each attachment now resolves independently from its own index.\n\n**What was not tested:** end-to-end channel ingestion through a live messaging provider (the fix is confined to the persisted-fields reader). The `MediaUrls` misalignment variant is covered by the unit suite rather than a live capture.\n\n## Tests and validation\n\nTwo regression tests added to `src/sessions/user-turn-transcript.test.ts` (the `MediaTypes` hole case and the `MediaUrls` hole case). Full file suite: **27/27 pass**. oxlint and tsgo clean on the changed file. The temporary proof spec shown above was removed after capturing the evidence; it is not part of the diff.\n",
        "branch": "fix/media-types-index-alignment",
